data.question: Can you help me understand if I need planning permission for roof installations and wall insulation in this given web content?

answers.answer: Roof installations such as solar panels, woodburning stoves, biomass boilers, and heat pumps may require planning permission based on certain conditions. For example, if the solar panels are installed on a main wall or side wall of the building in a conservation area, or if the external unit for heat pumps is visible from the road. Internal installations like woodburning stoves or biomass boilers that do not require a flue put onto the front or side of the property may not need planning permission. For complete details, it is best to refer to specific conditions outlined in the web content.

Wall insulation requirements depend on whether you have a cavity or solid wall. Internal cavity wall insulation does not need planning permission, but external wall insulation may require it if there will be a change in the building's appearance. For full details and conditions, it is best to refer to specific instructions outlined in the web content.
